Introduction

Background: The data consists of five economic time series, collected for the United States from the beginning of 1947 to the start of 2016. The data are recorded four times a year, or quarterly (so the basic unit of time is a quarter). These are . GDP (inflation adjusted) . Value of goods consumed (ditto) . Investment spending (ditto) . Total hours worked . Output per hour worked for all non-financial firms (inflation adjusted) Because most macroeconomic modelers do not concern themselves directly with these series, but only with their fluctuations around their long-run trends, all the series in the data set have been de-trended, and the data file contains the logged fluctuations around the trend. These give series are selected because of their importance to one of the foundational theories of modern macroeconomics, the real business cycle theory, which holds that the business cycle results from the economy reacting (optimally) to real shocks, which change what it is actually possible for the economy to produce, as opposed to monetary, financial or social causes. In the original and most widely-taught form of the theory, productivity is an exogenous variable, and the fluctuations in all other variables are ultimately driven by it. People (according to the theory) should work and invest more when they realize productivity has gone up, and more work and investment now should lead to more consump

1: A Model for Base Data

Comparisons

To determine which regression model to use here, we compare the error measurements of different techniques. Specifically, we check the mean squared errors and residual plots of generalized linear regression (gaussian family) and kernel regression. It is immediately apparent from the following residual plots that the residuals of kernel regression are much more evenly distributed on either side of the line, and that they suffer less change in spread across the graph (even though larger fitted values seem to be somewhat more variable). Numerical computation of the mean squared errors also reveals that kernel regression has much smaller errors overall, by a magnitude of 10^2.

library(np)

macro2005 <- subset(macro, X < "2006-01-01")

#Linear Regression
mac2005reg <- glm(GDP ~ Consumption+Investment+Hours+Productivity, 
                 data=macro2005)

kreg.macro <- npreg(GDP ~ Consumption+Investment+Hours+Productivity, 
                  data=macro2005)

Performance on Training Data

Now that we have settled on kernel regression, we can look at how the model fits the data. At bandwidths of 0.0055, 0.446, 0.0068, and 0.0055 for the consumption, investment, hours, and productivity variables at time t, we get the following output model coefficients for each variable. In this kernel regression, every predictive variable is important to the model. A plot of the kernel regression line and its standard error bounds at 3 standard deviations is shown as well. We can see that every point is captured by within 3 standard deviations of the model, and that the error margin is quite small in some places. While this tells us the model is accurate to data already seen, it also hints that overfitting may be occuring, as is often the case in kernel regression.

kreg.macro$bw
## [1] 0.005459 0.044641 0.006830 0.005511
summary(kreg.macro)
##

plot(macro2005$X, macro2005$GDP, main="Kernel Regression on Training Data w/ \n
     Std. Err. Intervals (3 Std. Deviations)", xlab="Date", ylab="GDP Change")
lines(macro2005$X, kreg.macro$mean, col="black")
lines(macro2005$X, kreg.macro$mean+3*kreg.macro$merr, col='red')
lines(macro2005$X, kreg.macro$mean-3*kreg.macro$merr, col='red')

Prediction Performances

In trying to predict post-2005 data we can see that our previous suspicion of overfitting is true. The model initially follows the points reasonably well, decreasing rapidly, but then evens out and predicts roughly the same value repeatedly as if it has hit a lower bound. While there is certainly overfitting taking place, this could also partly be the fault of poor training data; since the general trend of the pre-2005 data had been increasing, with no long-term dips, it makes sense that the kernel regression model would not easily handle this scenario.

post2005 <- na.omit(subset(macro, X > "2006-01-01"))
predicted <- predict(kreg.macro, newdata=post2005[, 3:6])

plot(macro$X, macro$GDP, main="Kernel Regression Predictions on \n
     Post-2005 Data", xlab="Date", ylab="GDP")
lines(macro2005$X, kreg.macro$mean, col="black")
points(post2005$X, post2005$GDP, col="blue")
lines(post2005$X, predicted)

2: A Model for Lagged Data

Comparisons

A new data frame is created to contain the data in lagged form, and again different models are compared on the merit of their error rates.
We can see that this time the generalized linear model (gaussian family) performs better it did than before relative to the kernel regression, with a much more even/less shaped spread in the residual plot and a MSE only slightly larger than the MSE of the kernel regression. The kernel regression, in turn, has a higher MSE than before, but seems to have improved in the residual plot with much less change in distribution of residuals for increasing fitted values. For the sake of comparison and since its MSE is still smaller, we will stick with kernel regression again here.

macroDelay <- macro[1:nrow(macro)-1,2:6]
macroDelay$GDP <- macro$GDP[2:nrow(macro)]
macroDelay$oldGDP <- macro$GDP[1:nrow(macro)-1]
macroDelay$X <- macro$X[2:nrow(macro)]

macroPost2005Delay <- na.omit(subset(macroDelay, X > "2006-01-01"))

Performance on Training Data

Again, we look at how the kernel model fits the data. At bandwidths of 0.0077, 0.0486, 22164, and 0.0081 for the consumption, investment, hours, and oldGDP variables at time t, we get the following output model. What is immediately clear in the output is that the hours variable has a massive bandwidth value, and is surely smoothed to the point of irrelevance. We might conclude that hours is thus not very influential/significant to the model. The other 3 predictive variables do seem to be important to the model. A plot of the kernel regression line and its standard error bounds at 3 standard deviations is shown as well. We can see that the majority of points are captured by within 3 standard deviations of the model, and that the error margin is again quite small in some places. We do see, however, that the error intervals and curve itself are much smoother in nature than before, without the spikes at peaks/dips present in the previous model. We might conclude that some overfitting is still occurring, but less overall.

Prediction Performances

Finally, we get to predicting the post-2005 points based on the new model. From the plot it is right away clear that this kernel regression is doing a significantly better job than the last one, with the line following the decrease until the end of the data. Close observation shows that the prediction line does even out a little towards the end, but this is not nearly as much of an issue as before. A quick calculation of the predicted points mean squared error yields 0.00022, which is perfectly reasonable.

predicted <- predict(kreg.delay, newdata=macroPost2005Delay)

plot(macro$X, macro$GDP, main="Kernel Regression Predictions on \n
     Post-2005 Data: t-1 Variables", xlab="Date", ylab="GDP")
lines(macro2005delay$X, kreg.delay$mean, col="black")
points(macroPost2005Delay$X, macroPost2005Delay$GDP, col="blue")
lines(macroPost2005Delay$X, predicted)

mean((predicted - macroPost2005Delay$GDP)^2)
## [1] 0.0002151

3: Testing the Productivity Variable as a Predictor

Comparisons (now with Productivity!)

When comparing the models with and without the Productivity variable, we start, as usual, with the residual plots. In both plots we see that the residuals with and without Productivity included for both linear and kernel regressions are roughly the same. A quick comparison of the MSEs of the linear/kernel models with/out Productivity confirms that the change in errors is minimal.

Performance on Training Data

Again, for the sake of comparison, we will look at the kernel regression models and compare the presence of Productivity to the absence of it. A quick comparison of bandwidths, as shown below, reveals that the addition of Productivity gives relevance to the Hours variable in the new model; whereas the old model had a bandwidth of over 20000, making Hours effectively irrelevant, the new model has a much more reasonable bandwidth of 0.0253 for Hours. This comes slightly at the expense of Consumption, Investment, and oldGDP, which each roughly double in bandwidth (but are still relevant). From this we might gather that Hours is correlated with Productivity, and that an interaction term may be relevant in future models. A simple plotting of the two kernel regressions on the pre-2005 data shows the curves are pretty similar, and that the Production-added model is just slightly smoother in shape.
Since it would be unclear to plot both sets of confidence intervals on the same full graphic, we will instead plot the standard errors alone. In this plot we see that the error rates match pretty closely for both models.

Prediction Performances

Finally, we compare the performances of the models with and without Productivity on the post-2005 data. Interestingly enough, based on the following plot the new model with Productivity added performs significantly worse than the previous model on the new data. The new one begins by following the datas fast decline like the old model, but then seems to deviate largely, though not as the first model (variables at time t) which yielded a horizontal line. The new model eventually catches back up to the data, but is clearly less accurate overall. This could

predictedAll <- predict(kreg.delayAll, newdata=macroPost2005Delay)

plot(macro$X, macro$GDP, main="Kernel Regression Predictions on Post-2005 Data: 
     t-1 Variables Orange-w/o Production, Purple-w/ Production",
     xlab="Date", ylab="GDP")
lines(macro2005delay$X, kreg.delay$mean, col="orange")
lines(macro2005delay$X, kreg.delayAll$mean, col="purple")
points(macroPost2005Delay$X, macroPost2005Delay$GDP, col="blue")
lines(macroPost2005Delay$X, predicted, col="orange")
lines(macroPost2005Delay$X, predictedAll, col="purple")

Overall, we can conclude from our findings that Productivity gives meaning to the Hours variable and helps smooth the model overall, but that Productivity actually worsens predictions when trained on the pre-2005 data. This indicates that the addition of this variable increases overfitting to some extent. It should not be taken away from this that productivity drives GDP on its own, at least not in the presence of the other variables utilized, even if Productivity does clearly have some effect on GDP.

4: Additive Regressions

Note that for both problems 4 and 5, we will continue to use pre-2005 data to train the models.

Summaries of the additive models are given below, including significance levels of the smoothed variables used. We can see that smoothed Productivity is significant when predicting future GDP (0.001 alpha), Investment (0.001 alpha), and Hours (0.1 alpha) levels, but not when predicting Consumption. Since Productivity is significant in predicting the future GDP model, these findings do support the theory that productivity drives GDP to some extent.

library(mgcv)

addGDP <- gam(GDP ~ s(oldGDP)+s(Consumption)+s(Investment)+s(Hours)+s(Productivity), 
              data=macro2005delay)

macro2005delay$newConsumption <- macro2005$Consumption[2:nrow(macro2005)]
addConsumption <- gam(newConsumption ~ s(oldGDP)+s(Consumption)+s(Investment)+s(Hours)+s(Productivity),
                      data=macro2005delay)

macro2005delay$newInvestment <- macro2005$Investment[2:nrow(macro2005)]
addInvestment <- gam(newInvestment ~ s(oldGDP)+s(Consumption)+s(Investment)+s(Hours)+s(Productivity),
                     data=macro2005delay)

macro2005delay$newHours <- macro2005$Hours[2:nrow(macro2005)]
addHours <- gam(newHours ~ s(oldGDP)+s(Consumption)+s(Investment)+s(Hours)+s(Productivity), 
                data=macro2005delay)

5: Estimating a First-Order Autoregressive Model for Productivity

AAR functions and dependencies.

design.matrix.from.ts <- function(ts, order, right.older = TRUE) {
  n <- length(ts)
  x <- ts[(order + 1):n]
  for (lag in 1:order) {
    if (right.older) {
      x <- cbind(x, ts[(order + 1 - lag):(n - lag)])
    }
    else {
      x <- cbind(ts[(order + 1 - lag):(n - lag)], x)
    }
  }
  lag.names <- c("lag0", paste("lag", 1:order, sep = ""))
  if (right.older) {
    colnames(x) <- lag.names
  }
  else {
    colnames(x) <- rev(lag.names)
  }
  return(as.data.frame(x))
}

aar <- function(ts, family=gaussian(), order) {
  stopifnot(require(mgcv))
  fit <- gam(as.formula(auto.formula(order)), 
             data=design.matrix.from.ts(ts, order), family=family)
  return(fit)
}
auto.formula <- function(order) {
  inputs <- paste("s(lag", 1:order, ")", sep = "", collapse = "+")
  form <- paste("lag0 ~ ", inputs)
return(form)
}

To model a first-order autoregressive model, functions from Shalizis chapter on Time Series are used. In the following code, several predictive methods are trained on pre-2005 data and compared via their ability to predict on post-2005 data, including AAR, kernel regression, and linear regression. When using only productivity at time t-1 as a predictor for productivity at time t, we find that a linear model yields the best predictive results at an MSE of 0.0000023. AAR does reasonably well at an MSE of 0.00059, but that is much worse than the linear model, clearly.

Based on our ability to make a pretty accurate model such as the above one from other predictors, we might conclude that Productivity is not an exogenous variable, but rather is endogenous to the dataset in nature.

7 (Concluding argument)

The statement Exogenous changes in productivity are the main driver of the macroeconomic fluctuations is one which is dubious at best, given the models we have observed here. As we saw in part 6, productivity itself is not exogenous in relation to the other variables in the macro dataset, which hints right away that there is some interconnectedness between all the endogenous variables. Inspection of models created in problems 1-4 showed that variables other than Productivity had statistically significant effects on estimating future GDP, in both kernel regression and GAM models. Thus, while exogenous changes in productivity do likely play a role in macroeconomic fluctuation, it would be unwise to attribute them as the main drivers of said fluctuation.
